  <content>
    <title>Jobs to Be Done (JTBD)</title>

    <summary>Framework for understanding why customers hire products. Produces job statements with functional, emotional, social dimensions and forces analysis. Jobs are stable; solutions evolve. 8-stage job map reveals where the job breaks down.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Product teams focused on features and demographics miss the underlying motivation. JTBD interviews with recent switchers — people who recently purchased, switched, or started using a category — reconstruct the decision timeline and reveal the real competition (often non-obvious: a task manager competes with sticky notes and email, not just Trello). Without JTBD, positioning copy speaks to features; with it, it speaks to the progress customers are trying to make.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Repositioning a product that has low conversion despite apparent feature completeness.</item>
        <item>Designing a new product category where obvious competitors don't exist yet.</item>
        <item>Understanding why customers churn when they "should" be satisfied.</item>
        <item>Rewriting positioning copy to speak to motivation, not features.</item>
        <item>Planning a switching campaign by mapping forces of progress for a competitor's customers.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Usability testing: JTBD explains why someone hired the product; usability testing explains why the product failed on the job.</item>
        <item>Quantitative feature prioritization: JTBD is qualitative and requires synthesis, not voting.</item>
        <item>When you have fewer than 5 recent switcher interviews — the framework needs pattern recognition across cases.</item>
        <item>When a LLM-generated job statement hasn't been validated with actual customers — synthetic JTBD is fiction.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="job-statement-formula">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Express every job as: "When [situation/trigger], I want to [action/motivation], so I can [outcome/expected result]." Capture all three components; a statement missing the situation is a feature request, not a job.</statement>
        <rationale>The situation anchors the job to a real trigger moment; without it, the statement describes an abstract desire that cannot be used to design a specific product experience.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>When I finish a client project, I want to send a professional invoice quickly, so I can get paid faster and move on to the next project. All three components present: trigger (finish client project), action (send invoice quickly), outcome (get paid faster).</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="three-job-dimensions">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every job has three dimensions: Functional (what task to accomplish), Emotional (how to feel), Social (how to be perceived). Capture all three; products that address only the functional dimension lose to products that also address emotional and social dimensions.</statement>
        <rationale>Customers who feel satisfied functionally but anxious emotionally or embarrassed socially will churn or avoid the product in high-stakes situations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Invoicing software: Functional = file a professional invoice; Emotional = feel confident I will get paid; Social = appear to be a legitimate business. A product addressing all three wins over one that just sends invoices.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="jobs-are-stable-solutions-evolve">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Identify the job, not the current solution; jobs persist across technology changes while solutions change. Compete at the job level, not the feature level.</statement>
        <rationale>Communicating distant family (job) has been done by letters, phone, email, and video calls — same job, radically different solutions. A product competing on features competes with current solutions; a product competing on the job owns the category across solution generations.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="four-forces-of-progress">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For a customer to switch, Push + Pull must outweigh Habit + Fear: Push = current pain driving away from old solution; Pull = new solution's appeal; Habit = comfort with the old way; Fear = anxiety about the new. All four forces must be assessed to predict adoption.</statement>
        <rationale>Products with strong pull but ignoring habit and fear launch to crickets; the switching cost is the sum of habit disruption and anxiety, not just the price difference.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="interview-recent-switchers">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Interview people who recently purchased, switched to a competitor, or started using a category — not long-tenured loyal customers. Recent switchers remember the decision; loyal customers have rationalized it.</statement>
        <rationale>Memory of the decision process fades within weeks; loyal customers reconstruct a coherent narrative that omits the actual friction and anxiety that drove the switch.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Ask "what did you use before?" before asking about the current product — the previous solution reveals the job better than the new one.</statement>
        <rationale>The job is defined by what was inadequate, not by what the customer currently values. The switch happened because the old solution failed the job.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="timeline-reconstruction">
      <p>Reconstruct the decision timeline across six stages: First Thought (trigger), Passive Looking (awareness), Active Looking (evaluation), Decision (purchase), Consumption (usage), Satisfaction (review).</p>
      <p>Key questions: "When did you first think you needed something different?" / "What was happening in your life at that point?" / "What did you try before this?" / "What almost stopped you from switching?"</p>
    </section>

    <section name="8-stage-job-map">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For complex jobs, map all 8 stages: Define, Locate, Prepare, Confirm, Execute, Monitor, Modify, Conclude. For each stage: customer goals, current pain points, opportunity for the product to help. Build the product around the highest-pain stages, not the core execution stage alone.</statement>
        <rationale>Most products address the Execute stage well but abandon the customer at Locate, Prepare, and Confirm — which are often the highest-friction points and the real differentiator.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="classic-jtbd-examples">
      <example type="good" title="Milkshake Job (Christensen)">
        <note>Commuters buying milkshakes at 7am. Surface understanding: they want breakfast. JTBD: "When I have a long boring commute, I want something to do with my hand that lasts 20 minutes, so I can make the drive less boring." Real competition: donuts, bananas, bagels, podcasts. Implication: make milkshake thicker and chunkier — a product insight invisible from demographic analysis.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Online Course JTBD">
        <note>Surface = "learn Python." Real job: "When I am stuck in a dead-end job, I want to gain a skill that is in demand, so I can switch careers and earn more money." Real competition: bootcamps, MBA, networking for promotion, starting a business. A Python course competing on curriculum loses; one competing on career change wins.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="common-jtbd-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Asking "what features do you want?" instead of "what are you trying to accomplish?"</description>
        <reason>Feature requests describe a solution hypothesis; job discovery requires understanding the progress the customer is trying to make, which is often different from what they explicitly request.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Building one job statement for all customers when different segments hire the product for different jobs.</description>
        <reason>A single product can be hired for multiple distinct jobs; conflating them into one statement produces positioning that speaks clearly to nobody.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-integration-limitations">
      <p>Agents cannot conduct JTBD timeline interviews — the method requires live follow-up probing. LLM-generated job statements are plausible but untested; every statement must be validated with actual customers. Forces analysis (push/pull/habit/fear) requires nuanced qualitative judgment that LLMs conflate into shallow lists. JTBD does not tell you what to build — it tells you what customers are trying to do; the solution design step remains human. Applying JTBD to B2B is complex: multiple stakeholders have different jobs; agents tend to collapse these into one.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>An agent can synthesize JTBD job statements from raw interview transcripts, draft the forces analysis matrix for a given product switch, and generate job maps for complex workflows. The most effective pattern is a two-pass synthesis: first the agent extracts raw quotes indexed by JTBD timeline stage, then a second pass refines quotes into structured job statements. Human review is mandatory before any job statement is used for strategic decisions.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent for executing JTBD research tasks in an SDD context. Any general Claude subagent for synthesizing interview transcripts into job statements and generating job maps.</p>
      <p>LLMs tend to generate generic job statements ("complete tasks efficiently") — instruct the agent to use the specific language from the transcript. The forces model requires tension analysis: push and pull must outweigh habit and fear for switching to occur; agents often list forces without assessing the balance. Do not use an agent to generate job statements without transcripts — synthetic JTBD is fiction. Human checkpoint: product/strategy decisions based on JTBD must be reviewed by someone who has spoken to real customers. Agents excel at the Locate and Execute stages of the job map (most structured) and struggle with Define and Confirm (most ambiguous).</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/job-statement.md" purpose="Job statement canvas with functional, emotional, and social dimensions."/>
      <template path="templates/jtbd-interview.md" purpose="Interview guide for recent switchers with forces analysis section."/>
      <template path="templates/job-map.md" purpose="8-stage job map template (goals, pain, opportunity per stage)."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-extract-statement.txt" purpose="LLM prompt to extract JTBD statement from an interview transcript."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-job-map.txt" purpose="LLM prompt to map a job statement into 8-stage framework."/>
      <template path="templates/jtbd-parser.py" purpose="Regex extractor for When/I want/So I can from raw interview notes."/>
    </templates>

